<promed@promedmail.org>

[This paper is tackling head-on the results of the misinformation campaigns surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic, with solid suggestions of actions needed to counteract these campaigns.

The study referred to by the National Bureau of Economic Research:
Bursztyn L, Rao A, Roth CP, Yanagizawa-Drott DH. Misinformation during a pandemic. NBER Working Paper No. 27417 June 2020, Revised September 2020; https://www.nber.org/papers/w27417
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Abstract
---------
"Media outlets often present diverging, even conflicting, perspectives on reality -- not only informing, but potentially misinforming audiences. We study the extent to which misinformation broadcast on mass media at the early stages of the coronavirus pandemic influenced health outcomes. We first document large differences in content between the 2 most popular cable news shows in the US, both on the same network, and in the adoption of preventative behaviors among viewers of these shows. Through both a selection-on-observables strategy and an instrumental variable approach, we find that areas with greater exposure to the show downplaying the threat of COVID-19 experienced a greater number of cases and deaths. We assess magnitudes through an epidemiological model highlighting the role of externalities and provide evidence that contemporaneous information exposure is a key underlying mechanism."

Globally the dangers of the infodemic have been recognized. The article above focuses on the USA, but similar infodemics have been permeating other countries, also with negative repercussions. WHO has recognized this and put together the 1st global infodemiology conference (https://www.who.int/news-room/events/detail/2020/06/30/default-calendar/1st-who-infodemiology-conference) and created an infodemiology management group (https://www.who.int/teams/risk-communication/infodemic-management). See https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-09-2020-managing-the-covid-19-infodemic-promoting-healthy-behaviours-and-mitigating-the-harm-from-misinformation-and-disinformation for a joint statement by WHO, the UN, UNICEF, UNDP, UNESCO, UNAIDS, ITU, UN Global Pulse, and IFRC on Managing the COVID-19 infodemic: Promoting healthy behaviours and mitigating the harm from misinformation and disinformation.

We have seen the resurgence of measles in many countries in response to an infodemic from the antivaccination movement. And the impact on the West African Ebola epidemic due to misinformation. Now we are seeing the impact of misinformation during a global emergency -- the COVID-19 pandemic, with devastating results. - Mod.MPP]

